408→                           A problem of Erdős and Sós, who also conjectured that every graph with at least\[\max\left( \binom{2k-1}{2}+1, (k-1)n-(k-1)^2+\binom{k-1}{2}+1\right)\]many edges contains every forest with $k$ edges. (Erdős and Gallai <a href="#cite-ErGa59-548" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGa59','548'); return false;">[ErGa59]</a> proved that this is the threshold which guarantees containing $k$ independent edges.)<br><br>It can be easily proved by induction that every graph on $n$ vertices with at least $n(k-1)+1$ edges contains every tree on $k+1$ vertices.<br><br>Brandt and Dobson <a href="#cite-BrDo96-548" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('BrDo96','548'); return false;">[BrDo96]</a> have proved this for graphs of girth at least $5$. Wang, Li, and Liu <a href="#cite-WLL00-548" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('WLL00','548'); return false;">[WLL00]</a> have proved this for graphs whose complements have girth at least $5$. Saclé and Woznik <a href="#cite-SaWo97-548" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('SaWo97','548'); return false;">[SaWo97]</a> have proved this for graphs which contain no cycles of length $4$. Yi and Li <a href="#cite-YiLi04-548" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('YiLi04','548'); return false;">[YiLi04]</a> have proved this for graphs whose complements contain no cycles of length $4$.<br><br>Implies <a href="/547" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[547]</a> and <a href="/557" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[557]</a>.<br><br>See also <a href="https://mathweb.ucsd.edu/~erdosproblems/erdos/newproblems/AllTreesSubgraphs.html" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">the entry in the graphs problem collection</a>.
